Solutions in PSO are encoded as n-tuples of real numbers. At the start of the method each particle is randomly placed in the n dimensional space. The methods’ core concept is that the particles are flown through \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{wasysym} 
\usepackage{amsfonts} 
\usepackage{amssymb} 
\usepackage{amsbsy}
\usepackage{upgreek}
\usepackage{mathrsfs}
\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
\begin{document}
}{}${\mathbb{R}}$\end{document}R in discrete time steps, and at each iteration the particles are responding to the quality factors of the best solution, being accelerated towards them. PSO keeps track of the overall best value, solution seen so far and the actual best value, solution present in the swarm. At each iteration, acceleration toward these solutions is weighted by random terms, in order to enable a better exploration of the solution space.

